{"title_page": "Netcomics", "text_new": "{{Notability|Companies|date=January 2010}}\n{{Infobox publisher\n| name         = NETCOMICS\n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| parent       = \n| status       = \n| traded_as    = \n| predecessor  = \n| founded      = 2005\n| founder      = Heewoon Chung\n| successor    = \n| country      = {{USA}}\n| headquarters = Los Angeles, California\n| distribution = [[Diamond Book Distributors]]<ref>[http://www.diamondbookdistributors.com/default.asp?t=2&m=1&c=53&s=660 Our Publishers]</ref>\n| keypeople    = \n| publications = [[manga]], <br /> [[manhwa]]\n| topics       = \n| genre        = [[Boy's Love]], Romance, Action\n| imprints     = \n| revenue      = \n| owner        = Heewoon Chung \n| numemployees = \n| website      = {{URL|www.netcomics.com}}\n}}\n\n'''NETCOMICS''' is a publisher of [[manhwa]], [[webtoons]], [[webcomics]], [[digital comics]], and [[manga]] [https://yattatachi.com/legal-online-manga-sites in] the United States, based in Los Angeles, CA, contributing to the [[Korean Wave]]. South Korean publisher [[Ecomix]] Media Company created NETCOMICS, with the first titles appearing in the first quarter of 2006.<ref>Cha, Kai-Ming. \"[http://www.netcomics.com/news/press_release.htm?uid=7 The Koreans Are Coming: NETCOMICS Brings Manhwa to U.S.: PW].\" Netcomics. December 6, 2005. Retrieved on December 9, 2011.</ref>\n\nNETCOMICS served as a distributor for some titles by manga publisher [[Aurora Publishing (United States)|Aurora Publishing]] until Aurora's closure in April 2010.<ref>http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2010-04-09/netcomics-to-remove-aurora-manga-on-april-14</ref>\n\nThey offer a huge variety of English titles that can be either rented or purchased on their homepage or app.[https://bookriot.com/2018/10/25/best-manga-reader-sites-and-apps/]\n\nIn particular, their international outreach is enormous.[https://animespiegel.de/blickpunkt-manga-legal-online-lesen/]\n\nBy offering several popular genres such as Boys Love, Romance, Drama, Fantasy, Comedy, Sci-Fi, thriller, and Action they compile a huge collection of popular titles.[https://www.netcomics.com/genre]\n\n<br />\n\n==Titles==\n*''[[0/6]]'' by [[Youjung Lee]]\n*''AEGIS'' by Jinha Yoo\n*''[[Dining Bar Akira]]'' by Tomoko Yamashita\n*''[[The Great Catsby]]'' by [[Doha Kang]]\n*''[[Let's Be Perverts]]'' by [[Youjung Lee]]\n*''[[Let Dai]]'' by Sooyeon Won\n*''[[Operation Liberate Men]]'' by [[Mira Lee]]\n*''[[Totally Captivated (manhwa)]]'' by Hajin Yoo\n*''[[X Diary]]'' by Toma\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|New Jersey|Comics|Anime and manga}}\n* [http://www.netcomics.com/ Official Site]\n\n[[Category:Manga distributors]]\n[[Category:Manhwa distributors]]\n\n\n{{manga-stub}}\n{{Manhwa-stub}}\n{{US-publish-company-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Notability|Companies|date=January 2010}}\n{{Infobox publisher\n| name         = NETCOMICS\n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| parent       = \n| status       = \n| traded_as    = \n| predecessor  = \n| founded      = 2005\n| founder      = Heewoon Chung\n| successor    = \n| country      = {{USA}}\n| headquarters = Los Angeles, California\n| distribution = [[Diamond Book Distributors]]<ref>[http://www.diamondbookdistributors.com/default.asp?t=2&m=1&c=53&s=660 Our Publishers]</ref>\n| keypeople    = \n| publications = [[manga]], <br /> [[manhwa]]\n| topics       = \n| genre        = [[Boy's Love]], Romance, Action\n| imprints     = \n| revenue      = \n| owner        = Heewoon Chung \n| numemployees = \n| website      = {{URL|www.netcomics.com}}\n}}\n\n'''NETCOMICS''' is a publisher of [[manhwa]], [[webtoons]], [[webcomics]], [[digital comics]], and [[manga]] [https://yattatachi.com/legal-online-manga-sites in] the United States, based in Los Angeles, CA, contributing to the [[Korean Wave]]. South Korean publisher [[Ecomix]] Media Company created NETCOMICS, with the first titles appearing in the first quarter of 2006.<ref>Cha, Kai-Ming. \"[http://www.netcomics.com/news/press_release.htm?uid=7 The Koreans Are Coming: NETCOMICS Brings Manhwa to U.S.: PW].\" Netcomics. December 6, 2005. Retrieved on December 9, 2011.</ref>\n\nNETCOMICS served as a distributor for some titles by manga publisher [[Aurora Publishing (United States)|Aurora Publishing]] until Aurora's closure in April 2010.<ref>http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2010-04-09/netcomics-to-remove-aurora-manga-on-april-14</ref>\n\nThey offer a huge variety of English titles that can be either rented or purchased on their homepage or app.[https://bookriot.com/2018/10/25/best-manga-reader-sites-and-apps/]\n\nIn particular, their international outreach is gaining more and more recognition.[https://animespiegel.de/blickpunkt-manga-legal-online-lesen/]\n\nBy offering several popular genres such as Boys Love, Romance, Drama, Fantasy, Comedy, Sci-Fi, thriller, and Action they compile a huge collection of popular titles.[https://www.netcomics.com/genre]\n\n<br />\n\n==Titles==\n*''[[0/6]]'' by [[Youjung Lee]]\n*''AEGIS'' by Jinha Yoo\n*''[[Dining Bar Akira]]'' by Tomoko Yamashita\n*''[[The Great Catsby]]'' by [[Doha Kang]]\n*''[[Let's Be Perverts]]'' by [[Youjung Lee]]\n*''[[Let Dai]]'' by Sooyeon Won\n*''[[Operation Liberate Men]]'' by [[Mira Lee]]\n*''[[Totally Captivated (manhwa)]]'' by Hajin Yoo\n*''[[X Diary]]'' by Toma\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|New Jersey|Comics|Anime and manga}}\n* [http://www.netcomics.com/ Official Site]\n\n[[Category:Manga distributors]]\n[[Category:Manhwa distributors]]\n\n\n{{manga-stub}}\n{{Manhwa-stub}}\n{{US-publish-company-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Maria97531", "label": "safe", "comment": "better description of company", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Netcomics"}
{"title_page": "12.38", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name          = 12.38\n| type          = song\n| released      =\n| artist        = [[Childish Gambino]]\n| album         = [[3.15.20]]\n| genre         = \n| length        = {{Duration|m=6|s=32}}\n| writer        = {{hlist|[[Donald Glover]]|[[DJ Dahi|Dacoury Natche]]|[[21 Savage|Sh\u00e9yaa Bin Abraham-Joseph]]|Atia \"Ink\" Boggs|[[Kadhja Bonet]]}}\n| producer      = {{hlist|D. Glover|[[DJ Dahi]]}}\n| misc          = {{Audio sample\n | type        = song\n | file        = Childish Gambino 12-38.ogg}}}}\n\"'''12.38'''\" is a song by American rapper [[Donald Glover|Childish Gambino]] from his fourth studio album ''[[3.15.20]]'' (2020).<ref name=\"P4k\">{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/childish-gambino-1238/|title=\"12.38\" by Childish Gambino Review|author=Noah Yoo|accessdate=April 2, 2020|date=March 24, 2020|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325194050/https://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/childish-gambino-1238/|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Genius\">{{Cite web|title=21 Savage Raps About Police Harassment On Childish Gambino\u2019s \"12.38\"|url=https://genius.com/a/21-savage-raps-about-police-harassment-on-childish-gambino-s-12-38|website=[[Genius (website)|Genius]]|date=March 22, 2020|accessdate=April 2, 2020|author1=Eddie Fu|author2=Tia Hill|author3=Joe Ali}}</ref> The song features uncredited vocals by rapper [[21 Savage]] and American musicians [[Kadhja Bonet]] and background vocals by American singer-songwriter Atia \"Ink\" Boggs. The song was produced by Gambino, credited as Donald Glover, along with [[DJ Dahi]]. Gaminbo sings about a [[psilocybin]] trip with a girl, while 21 Savage raps about police harassment. Critics praised the song's comedic narrative and 21 Savage's guest appearance. \n\n==Background==\nIn 2018, Gambino and American rapper [[21 Savage]] collaborated together on Gambino's single \"[[This Is America (song)|This Is America]]\" and the track \"Monster\" from 21 Savage's second studio album ''[[I Am Greater than I Was|I Am > I Was]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.coolaccidents.com/news/heres-everyone-who-features-on-childish-gambinos-this-is-america|title=Here's Everyone Who Features On Childish Gambino's 'This Is America'|date=May 7, 2018|accessdate=April 2, 2020|website=Cool Accidents}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/music/a25653251/childish-gambino-21-savage-monster-lyrics-verse/|title=Childish Gambino's Verse on 21 Savage's 'Monster' Explains Why He Wants to Retire From Music|website=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]|date=December 21, 2018|accessdate=April 2, 2020|author=Matt Miller}}</ref> Producer [[DJ Dahi]] called the creation of the song an evolving process.<ref name=\"Dahi\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/childish-gambino-album-dj-dahi-interview-970222/|title=Donald Glover\u2019s Surprise Album Is a Mystery. DJ Dahi Has (Some) Answers|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=April 3, 2020|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|author=Elias Leight}}</ref> Dahi had an initial beat with chords provided by Ely Rise.<ref name=\"Dahi\"/> [[Kadhja Bonet]]'s vocals were for another track, but were [[Chopping (sampling technique)|chopped]] and reused for \"12.38\".<ref name=\"Dahi\"/> Dahi described the track as having \"funky, odd, but feels good\" energy. The song was momentarily put to the side, but Gambino continued writing his verse.<ref name=\"Dahi\"/> 21 Savage recorded his guest verse and Atia \"Ink\" Boggs was invited to co-write.<ref name=\"Dahi\"/> The song originally surfaced under the unofficial title \"Vibrate\" when Gambino streamed ''3.15.20'' on his website on March 15, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hiphop-n-more.com/2020/03/donald-glover-childish-gambino-new-album-stream/|title=Donald Glover Releases New Album Through Live Stream|date=March 15, 2020|accessdate=April 2, 2020|website=HipHop-N-More|author=NavJosh}}</ref> The track was titled \"12.38\" upon the album's official release on March 22, 2020.\n\n==Composition and lyrics==\n[[File:Psilocybe semilanceata 6514.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Gambino sings about a girl feeding him [[psilocybin]], though he is unaware of the drug's effects (''[[Psilocybe semilanceata]]'' pictured).]]\nNoah Yoo of ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' described the production of \"12.38\" as a \"sensual, minimalistic bounce.\"<ref name=\"P4k\"/> The song interpolates [[Andr\u00e9 3000]]'s song \"[[Speakerboxxx/The Love Below|Vibrate]]\".<ref name=\"P4k\"/> In the song, a girl feeds Gambino [[psilocybin]], who is unfamiliar with the drug.<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/mar/28/childish-gambino-31520-review-a-deep-dive-made-for-self-isolation|title=Childish Gambino: 3.15.20 review \u2013 a deep-dive made for self-isolation|website=[[The Guardian]]|author=Kitty Empire|accessdate=April 3, 2020|date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> Sexual tension builds up as Gambino's girlfriend keeps texting him, causing his phone to vibrate.<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> Gambino uses humorous lines such as \"Why your cat looking at me sideways?\" in place of a hook and chorus.<ref name=\"P4k\"/> Gambino's verse continues as a beat-by-beat breakdown of the psilocybin use, until he wakes up alone.<ref name=\"Sputnik\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/81088/Childish-Gambino-03.15.20/|title=Review: Childish Gambino - 03.15.20|website=[[Sputnikmusic]]|date=March 30, 2020|author=Rowan5215|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref> Gambino name-checks multiple female artists, including [[Toni Braxton]], [[SZA (singer)|SZA]], and [[Chaka Khan]].<ref name=\"P4k\"/> 21 Savage raps police harassment; he was previously detained by [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement]] in February 2019.<ref name=\"Genius\"/> By the end, the song \"devolves into spirals of vocal echoes\" as a result of a psilocybin trip kicking in.<ref name=\"P4k\"/>\n\n==Critical reception==\nKitty Empire of ''[[The Guardian]]'' called the song excellent and described it as having \"the feel of narrative fiction\". Empire stated that the song \"could be an episode of ''[[Atlanta (TV series)|Atlanta]]'',\" an American comedy-drama television series created by Gambino. Rowan5215 of ''[[Sputnikmusic]]'' called the song hilarious and wrote that \"Gambino [weaponizes] his full range to spin some ''[[The Love Below]]''-style seduction.\" Okla Jones of ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'' called the song witty and sonically-pleasing as Gambino \"taps into his prowess as both a writer and a comic.\"<ref name=\"COS\">{{Cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/03/album-review-childish-gambino-03-15-20/|title=Childish Gambino\u2019s 3.15.20 Revels in Its Perfect Timing|author=Okla Jones|accessdate=April 3, 2020|website=[[Consequence of Sound]]|date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Jones wrote that 21 Savage's verse had [[Southern United States|Southern]] charm and was must-needed.<ref name=\"COS\"/> Noah Yoo of ''Pitchfork'' praised 21 Savage's \"particularly on point\" guest appearance.<ref name=\"P4k\"/> Yoo wrote that as the song ends in spiraling echoes, \"it\u2019s 21\u2019s lyrics you\u2019re left thinking about.\"<ref name=\"P4k\"/>\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/134981147/credits|title=Credits / 3.15.20 / Childish Gambino \u2013 TIDAL|website=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Donald Glover|Childish Gambino]] \u2013 lead artist, producer, lyricist, composer\n* Atia \"Ink\" Boggs \u2013 background vocals, lyricist, composer\n* [[21 Savage]] \u2013 uncredited vocals, lyricist, composer\n* [[Kadhja Bonet]] \u2013 uncredited vocals, lyricist, composer\n* [[DJ Dahi]] \u2013 producer, lyricist, composer\n* Chukwudi Hodge \u2013 drums\n* Kurtis McKenzie \u2013 drums\n* Carlos \"Loshendrix\" Munoz \u2013 guitar\n* Ely Rise \u2013 keyboards\n* James Francies, Jr. \u2013 synthesizers\n* Riley Mackin \u2013 recording, mixing\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Childish Gambino}}\n{{21 Savage}}\n\n[[Category:2020 songs]]\n[[Category:Donald Glover songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Donald Glover]]\n[[Category:Songs written by 21 Savage]]\n[[Category:Songs about drugs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name          = 12.38\n| type          = song\n| released      =\n| artist        = [[Childish Gambino]]\n| album         = [[3.15.20]]\n| genre         = \n| length        = {{Duration|m=6|s=32}}\n| writer        = {{hlist|[[Donald Glover]]|[[DJ Dahi|Dacoury Natche]]|[[21 Savage|Sh\u00e9yaa Bin Abraham-Joseph]]|Atia \"Ink\" Boggs|[[Kadhja Bonet]]}}\n| producer      = {{hlist|D. Glover|[[DJ Dahi]]}}\n| misc          = {{Audio sample\n | type        = song\n | file        = Childish Gambino 12-38.ogg}}}}\n\"'''12.38'''\" is a song by American rapper [[Donald Glover|Childish Gambino]] from his fourth studio album ''[[3.15.20]]'' (2020).<ref name=\"P4k\">{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/childish-gambino-1238/|title=\"12.38\" by Childish Gambino Review|author=Noah Yoo|accessdate=April 2, 2020|date=March 24, 2020|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325194050/https://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/childish-gambino-1238/|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Genius\">{{Cite web|title=21 Savage Raps About Police Harassment On Childish Gambino\u2019s \"12.38\"|url=https://genius.com/a/21-savage-raps-about-police-harassment-on-childish-gambino-s-12-38|website=[[Genius (website)|Genius]]|date=March 22, 2020|accessdate=April 2, 2020|author1=Eddie Fu|author2=Tia Hill|author3=Joe Ali}}</ref> The song features uncredited vocals by rapper [[21 Savage]] and American musicians [[Kadhja Bonet]] and background vocals by American singer-songwriter Atia \"Ink\" Boggs. The song was produced by Gambino, credited as Donald Glover, along with [[DJ Dahi]]. Gaminbo sings about a [[psilocybin]] trip with a girl, while 21 Savage raps about police harassment. Critics praised the song's comedic narrative and 21 Savage's guest appearance. \n\n==Background==\nIn 2018, Gambino and American rapper [[21 Savage]] collaborated together on Gambino's single \"[[This Is America (song)|This Is America]]\" and the track \"Monster\" from 21 Savage's second studio album ''[[I Am Greater than I Was|I Am > I Was]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.coolaccidents.com/news/heres-everyone-who-features-on-childish-gambinos-this-is-america|title=Here's Everyone Who Features On Childish Gambino's 'This Is America'|date=May 7, 2018|accessdate=April 2, 2020|website=Cool Accidents}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/music/a25653251/childish-gambino-21-savage-monster-lyrics-verse/|title=Childish Gambino's Verse on 21 Savage's 'Monster' Explains Why He Wants to Retire From Music|website=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]|date=December 21, 2018|accessdate=April 2, 2020|author=Matt Miller}}</ref> Producer [[DJ Dahi]] called the creation of the song an evolving process.<ref name=\"Dahi\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/childish-gambino-album-dj-dahi-interview-970222/|title=Donald Glover\u2019s Surprise Album Is a Mystery. DJ Dahi Has (Some) Answers|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=April 3, 2020|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|author=Elias Leight}}</ref> Dahi had an initial beat with chords provided by Ely Rise.<ref name=\"Dahi\"/> [[Kadhja Bonet]]'s vocals were for another track, but were [[Chopping (sampling technique)|chopped]] and reused for \"12.38\".<ref name=\"Dahi\"/> Dahi described the track as having \"funky, odd, but feels good\" energy. The song was momentarily put to the side, but Gambino continued writing his verse.<ref name=\"Dahi\"/> 21 Savage recorded his guest verse and Atia \"Ink\" Boggs was invited to co-write.<ref name=\"Dahi\"/> The song originally surfaced under the unofficial title \"Vibrate\" when Gambino streamed ''3.15.20'' on his website on March 15, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hiphop-n-more.com/2020/03/donald-glover-childish-gambino-new-album-stream/|title=Donald Glover Releases New Album Through Live Stream|date=March 15, 2020|accessdate=April 2, 2020|website=HipHop-N-More|author=NavJosh}}</ref> The track was titled \"12.38\" upon the album's official release on March 22, 2020.\n\n==Composition and lyrics==\n[[File:Psilocybe semilanceata 6514.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Gambino sings about a girl feeding him [[psilocybin]], though he is unaware of the drug's effects (''[[Psilocybe semilanceata]]'' pictured).]]\nNoah Yoo of ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' described the production of \"12.38\" as a \"sensual, minimalistic bounce.\"<ref name=\"P4k\"/> The song interpolates [[Andr\u00e9 3000]]'s song \"[[Speakerboxxx/The Love Below|Vibrate]]\".<ref name=\"P4k\"/> In the song, a girl feeds Gambino [[psilocybin]], who is unfamiliar with the drug.<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/mar/28/childish-gambino-31520-review-a-deep-dive-made-for-self-isolation|title=Childish Gambino: 3.15.20 review \u2013 a deep-dive made for self-isolation|website=[[The Guardian]]|author=Kitty Empire|accessdate=April 3, 2020|date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> Sexual tension builds up as Gambino's girlfriend keeps texting him, causing his phone to vibrate.<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> Gambino uses humorous lines such as \"Why your cat looking at me sideways?\" in place of a hook and chorus.<ref name=\"P4k\"/> Gambino's verse continues as a beat-by-beat breakdown of the psilocybin use, until he wakes up alone.<ref name=\"Sputnik\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/81088/Childish-Gambino-03.15.20/|title=Review: Childish Gambino - 03.15.20|website=[[Sputnikmusic]]|date=March 30, 2020|author=Rowan5215|accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref> Gambino name-checks multiple female artists, including [[Toni Braxton]], [[SZA]], and [[Chaka Khan]].<ref name=\"P4k\"/> 21 Savage raps police harassment; he was previously detained by [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement]] in February 2019.<ref name=\"Genius\"/> By the end, the song \"devolves into spirals of vocal echoes\" as a result of a psilocybin trip kicking in.<ref name=\"P4k\"/>\n\n==Critical reception==\nKitty Empire of ''[[The Guardian]]'' called the song excellent and described it as having \"the feel of narrative fiction\". Empire stated that the song \"could be an episode of ''[[Atlanta (TV series)|Atlanta]]'',\" an American comedy-drama television series created by Gambino. Rowan5215 of ''[[Sputnikmusic]]'' called the song hilarious and wrote that \"Gambino [weaponizes] his full range to spin some ''[[The Love Below]]''-style seduction.\" Okla Jones of ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'' called the song witty and sonically-pleasing as Gambino \"taps into his prowess as both a writer and a comic.\"<ref name=\"COS\">{{Cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/03/album-review-childish-gambino-03-15-20/|title=Childish Gambino\u2019s 3.15.20 Revels in Its Perfect Timing|author=Okla Jones|accessdate=April 3, 2020|website=[[Consequence of Sound]]|date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Jones wrote that 21 Savage's verse had [[Southern United States|Southern]] charm and was must-needed.<ref name=\"COS\"/> Noah Yoo of ''Pitchfork'' praised 21 Savage's \"particularly on point\" guest appearance.<ref name=\"P4k\"/> Yoo wrote that as the song ends in spiraling echoes, \"it\u2019s 21\u2019s lyrics you\u2019re left thinking about.\"<ref name=\"P4k\"/>\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/134981147/credits|title=Credits / 3.15.20 / Childish Gambino \u2013 TIDAL|website=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Donald Glover|Childish Gambino]] \u2013 lead artist, producer, lyricist, composer\n* Atia \"Ink\" Boggs \u2013 background vocals, lyricist, composer\n* [[21 Savage]] \u2013 uncredited vocals, lyricist, composer\n* [[Kadhja Bonet]] \u2013 uncredited vocals, lyricist, composer\n* [[DJ Dahi]] \u2013 producer, lyricist, composer\n* Chukwudi Hodge \u2013 drums\n* Kurtis McKenzie \u2013 drums\n* Carlos \"Loshendrix\" Munoz \u2013 guitar\n* Ely Rise \u2013 keyboards\n* James Francies, Jr. \u2013 synthesizers\n* Riley Mackin \u2013 recording, mixing\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Childish Gambino}}\n{{21 Savage}}\n\n[[Category:2020 songs]]\n[[Category:Donald Glover songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Donald Glover]]\n[[Category:Songs written by 21 Savage]]\n[[Category:Songs about drugs]]\n", "name_user": "Nice4What", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eComposition and lyrics:Disamb", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/12.38"}
